observations.recommendation:
We have recommended that Management:

	Conduct a complete physical inventory of the Land Improvement projects implemented by the LGU; 


	Reconcile the Land improvement account with the Physical Inventory Report and the  reports of the Accounting Unit;


Update the PPE Ledger Cards of the Municipal Accounting Unit on the  Land Improvement account; and 

	Ensure that the corresponding Accumulated Depreciation account is also adjusted accordingly.

We have recommended that Management:

Require the GSO-Designate to strictly comply with the required physical count of all properties at least once a year using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;

Require the GSO-Designate to maintain Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property Ledger Cards and be reconciled with the Property Cards of the GSO-Designate;

Require the GSO-Designate to adopt a uniform property identification system for PPE wherein a unique Property Number shall be assigned for each item and on which the Property Number shall be prominently shown in the property sticker, showing all the vital information of the PPE to facilitate a methodological system of inventory-taking and to strengthen internal control on PPE; and

Monitor closely the implementation of Executive Order No. 07, series of 2023 re: Reorganizing the Municipal Property Inventory, Appraisal and Disposal Committee in the Municipal Government of Sto. Tomas, Pangasinan, to spearhead the conduct of the One-Time Cleansing of PPEs pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that:

a) The Inventory Committee shall conduct semestral physical inventory of supplies and prepare the corresponding RPCI, and reconcile the same with the property and accounting records. It shall then be submitted to the Auditor pursuant to Section 124, Volume I of NGAS Manual for LGUs;

b) The General Services Office thru its supply and property officer prepares and maintains SCs for each type of supplies and materials while its Accounting Office maintains SLCs for each supply and materials acquired and issued to support the year-end balances of the supplies and materials inventory and expense accounts in the financial statements;

c) The supply and property officer consolidate weekly/monthly the RIS for which supplies and materials  were issued using the SSMI. Submit the SSMI supported by RIS to the Accountant for recording pursuant to Section 121, Volume I of NGAS Manual for LGUs; and

d) The property officer revisit and review of the LGU’s existing policies and procedures with regard to inventory process, which must be followed as a control procedure of inventory as required and provided under Section 122, Volume 1 of NGAS Manual for LGUs.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations and made additional recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require officials concerned to:
(a) implement the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), recognition of PPE found at the station, and disposition of non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances as laid out in COA Circular 2020-006;
(b) exert efforts to prepare the Property Cards and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards, respectively, starting with the current year’s acquisition and recent years’ acquisitions and aim for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPE items are covered;
(c) consider the creation of a permanent position in the GSO and accounting office to carry out regular functions, particularly the conduct of annual physical count and maintenance of property records;
(d) attend training relative to LRAMM by the DILG, to be able to adopt and follow the procedures set forth therein and eventually comply with the requirements thereof on reporting as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008;
(e) prepare an Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property and Report of Waste Materials, where applicable, for unserviceable properties and request the same for disposal in accordance with the procedures mentioned above; and
(f) cause the designation of new members of the Inventory Committee in replacement of the former members who are separated from service for the improved efficiency and compliance of the Committee.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
(a) examine the books of accounts and confirm the declared gross receipts with other government agencies in the renewal of business licenses of taxpayers to verify the accuracy of the declared gross receipts;
(b) maintain copies of the proof of gross receipts, if available, to support the assessed amount of taxes;
(c) establish a stratified schedule to set a certain income level standard for various business entities after careful consideration of various industry factors as the basis for a presumptive income level to be embodied in the Municipality’s local tax ordinance; and
(d) exert additional efforts to cause the full implementation of e-BOSS to increase efficiency in the revenue collection of the LGU.

10.26 We recommended the LCE to:
a. Issue a memorandum requiring all AOs to strictly liquidate their cash advances within the timeframe prescribed under COA Circular No. 97-002; and
b. Institute sanctions in accordance with CSC MC No. 23 s. 2019 for non-compliance thereof, if deemed appropriate.
We also recommended the LCE to direct the MA to:
a. Reclassify the ₱1,433,044.59 to Other Receivables account and subsequently furnish the Journal Entry Voucher to the AT for validation;
b. In the absence of available supporting documents for the unliquidated cash advances amounting to ₱1,433,044.59, initiate the necessary procedures of write-off as provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005;
c. Immediately issue final written reminders/demand letters, duly signed by the LCE, to the erring accountable officers, requiring them to liquidate their outstanding cash advances through the submission of valid and complete liquidation reports;
d. Ensure that a duly signed certification stating that previous cash advances have been liquidated and properly accounted for in the books is attached, as required under COA Circular No. 2012-001; and
e. Conduct quarterly verification, analysis and validation of all outstanding unliquidated cash advances to ensure accurate reporting and timely liquidation.

14.8 We recommended the LCE to instruct the:
a. MA to thoroughly trace and analyze the details of the outstanding balances in the Due to GSIS, Due to HDMF and Due to PHIC accounts, and initiate appropriate corrective actions, such as processing refund claims for over-withheld amounts or withholding any under-remitted contributions from employee salaries, as applicable;
b. HRMO Designate to expedite the re-publication of the vacant HRMO II position to facilitate the eventual transfer of payroll preparation back to the HRM Office;
c. MA to formally turn over the preparation of payroll documents, including the computation of mandatory deductions, to the HRM Office upon the successful filling of the HRMO II position, to ensure proper segregation of duties; and
d. Accounting and HRM Offices to establish close coordination in the preparation and processing of payrolls. Specifically, the HRMO shall be responsible for the preparation of payroll documents, while the MA shall conduct a thorough review to ensure accuracy and compliance with applicable rules and regulations, thereby reinforcing internal control in the payroll process.

20.12 We recommended the LCE the following recommendations:
a. Require end-users to use RIS in requesting supplies;
b. Constitute an Inventory Committee who will be responsible for the conduct of semi-annual inventory taking of all inventory items and for the preparation of the required Report on the Physical Count of Inventory (RPCI), to be submitted to the AT;
c. For the office supplies, direct the MT to safekeep the inventories, maintain SCs, and regularly prepare the SSMI, and provide a copy to the Accounting Office;
d. For the medical supplies, designate a custodian from the RHU who will be responsible for the safekeeping the stocks, maintenance of SCs and preparation SSMI to be submitted to the Accounting Office; and
e. Direct the MA to maintain SLCs, to be reconciled with the records of the MT, and the RPCI to ascertain the accuracy of inventory balances and determine discrepancies that require immediate adjustment.

21.9 We recommended that the LCE direct the:
a. MA, in coordination with all department heads, to propose and implement a policy establishing a cut-off date for the acceptance and processing of claims, to ensure the timely recognition of obligations and compliance with applicable tax withholding and financial reporting requirements;
b. BAC to exert its best effort to optimize the full 12-month procurement period and avoid the concentration of procurement activities toward year-end, thereby minimizing the late lodging of procurement claims and ensuring timely processing and reporting of obligations;
c. MT to regularly submit all paid claims to the Accounting Office in a timely manner to prevent delays in the preparation of financial reports and to ensure the smooth execution of other accounting processes; and
d. MA to withhold the applicable taxes at the time the expenses are accrued and remit the same to the BIR within the prescribed period in compliance with RR No. 04-2024.

22.13 We recommended the LCE to direct the ME to:
a. Ensure strict adherence to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004, dated January 30, 2013, by enforcing full compliance among contractors with the requirement to post project signboards at each infrastructure site, containing all relevant details and information. Additionally, the project status must be regularly updated and maintained according to the schedule set forth in the Circular;
b. Ensure that the materials specified and programmed for the project billboards are actually used or installed, and the pay item accurately computed;
c. Ensure that only the actual accomplishments are reported in the SWA for each inspected project. In cases where project signboards are not installed, the cost of installation of signboards should not be included as part of the reported accomplishments to avoid misrepresentation and overstatement of project progress;
d. Submit proof of posting for the remaining 16 projects mentioned, otherwise, require the contractors to refund the amounts charged, as follows:

22.14 Lastly, the AT recommended that Management promptly notify both the SA and the ATL within 10 days after the award of an infrastructure project, or prior to the commencement of any related program or activity, confirming that the appropriate project signboards have been posted, as required under 3.1 of the COA Circular.

We have recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Verify the validity of payables aged two years and more, send confirmation letters for balances with identified claimants or creditors, and remunerate all valid claims. Otherwise, cause the reversion of the payables to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund;
Exert effort to retrieve the documents of unidentified Other Payables or those without details in the subsidiary ledgers for proper classification of the recorded amount;
Prepare the Aging of Payables to monitor any outstanding accounts payable to suppliers and to facilitate payment; and
Provide clarity on the descriptions/particulars of items presented in the Schedule of Due from Other Funds, Due to NGAs, Due to Other Funds, and Other Payables under the Trust Fund, as it could not be linked to corresponding liability transactions.

We have recommended that Management:
Establish structured measures for officials/officers and emloyees of the LGU upon resignation or retirement from the service to facilitate a smooth transition of accountabilities, which includes proper turnover of essential records, reports, and other documents for effective discharge of duty of the incoming officer/official/employees, and also to prevent similar lapses from occurring in the future;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property Cards and Property Ledger Cards for each PPE item, ensuring that these records are reconciled properly;
Implement the One-Time Cleansing of PPEs pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability; and
Direct the Disposal/Appraisal Committee headed by the Municipal Treasurer, as General Service Officer (GSO) of the LGU,  to conduct and manage the disposal process which includes the preparation of appraisal reports and other required documents to facilitate the disposal of the unserviceable properties following the procedures set forth under Section 379 of Republic Act (R.A.) No. 7160, Section 167 of COA Circular No. 92-386 and Section 79 of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445. Likewise, upon disposal, ensure that these properties are derecognized in the books of accounts for proper presentation of the PPE accounts in the financial statements.

We have recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to perform the following courses of action:
Ensure that cash advances granted to elected officials are limited only to their own official travel;
Use the appropriate advance accounts to record cash advances pursuant to the Revised Chart of Accounts;
Provide a certification among the additional documents for cash advance transactions, confirming that the official or employee requesting the cash advance has no outstanding cash advances; and
Monitor the liquidation of cash advances and ensure that these are liquidated as soon as the purpose for which it was granted has been served.

We have recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Ensure that cashbooks are regularly footed and certified at the end of each month;
Provide the reference documents under the “Reference” column in the Cashbook in adherence to Sections 26 to 29 of Chapter 1, Volume II of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs;
Use the RCD format prescribed under Section 49, Chapter 2, and Annex 41, Volume II of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, and ensure to fill up accordingly. Report any undeposited collections, if any, under Section D of the report or the Summary of Collections and Remittances/Deposits;
Ensure completeness and correctness of the RAAF and submit monthly the CRAAF to the audit team; and
Use the RCD format prescribed under Section 55, Chapter 2, and Annex 47, Volume II of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, and ensure that it is filled out in accordance with the given instructions. Likewise, use the certification prescribed by the Manual.

We have recommended that Management:
Require all department heads to submit PPMP to be consolidated into an APP by the Bid and Awards Committee (BAC) Secretariat;
Require the Municipal Treasurer as the General Services Officer (GSO) of the LGU to consolidate the 2-month requirement for the procurement of commonly used supplies through the preparation of the consolidated PR on a bi-monthly basis based on the consolidated PPMP and APP;
Instruct the BAC to strictly adopt public or competitive bidding as the primary mode of procurement, in accordance with the provisions of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184, to ensure transparency, accountability, and the attainment of the most advantageous terms for the government; and
Advise department heads to refrain from preparing PRs as needs arise, except in cases of duly justified emergencies. All requisitions for commonly used supplies should be routed through the Municipal Treasurer/GSO, who will oversee the preparation of consolidated PRs, ensure proper safekeeping, and monitor inventory levels to maintain effective control and accountability of supplies.

1.46. We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations and supplemented additions thereto and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
(a) requires officials concerned to attend training relative to LRAMM by the DILG, to be able to adopt and follow the procedures set forth therein and eventually comply with the requirements thereof on reporting as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008;
(b) instruct the Acting-GSO to prepare the Property Cards, Local Road Inventory and Road Map and Local Road Network Card, and the and Acting Municipal Accountant to exert efforts in preparing Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards, starting with the current year’s acquisition and aiming for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPEs are covered;
(c) consider the creation of a permanent position in the GSO and accounting office to carry out regular functions, particularly the conduct of annual physical count and maintenance of property records;
(d) cause the reconstitution of the Inventory Committee for the inclusion of a staff member of the Accounting Office as part of the committee as required by COA Circular No. 2020-006; and
(e) through the reconstituted inventory committee prepare an Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property and Report of Waste Materials, where applicable, for unserviceable properties mentioned above.
1.47. We further recommended and the LCE agreed to:
(f) enjoin the Inventory Committee and other concerned officials to henceforth, conduct periodic inventory as required by the MNGAS to avoid the recurrence of discrepancies in the PPE records of the LGU; and
(g) instruct the Acting-Municipal Accountant to undertake the reclassification of the assets that meet the recognition criteria of semi-expendable properties.

We reiterated and supplemented our prior year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
(a) LDC, MPDO along with the Municipal Budget Officer, to (i) submit a written justification and, if possible, supporting documents for the identified variance between the amount in the original budget and the submitted utilization report; and (ii) ensure that the allotted budget for the fund does not fall below the required amount;
(b) present in detail the PPAs charged under the 20% DF in the Annual Investment Program (AIP);
(c) continuously refer to the abovementioned JMCs for appropriate guidance in crafting the Annual Investment Program and inclusion of PPAs in the 20% DF that will aim to fully attain the desired socio-economic development targets of the Municipality, with emphasis on the recent issuance on the utilization of the fund and inclusion of budget intended for the implementation of CBMS to aid in planning PPAs in the Municipality; and
(d) observe continued adherence with the mandated utilization of the fund and checking/regular monitoring thereof in harmony with the approved AIP in accordance with pertinent provisions of the JMCs cited above.

We reiterated our previous year’s and made additional recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to, thru the Designated MENRO to:
(a) intensify and sustain the current information drive and awareness campaign among the residents, in coordination with the Barangay, following the strategies identified under the approved 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan of the LGU and with focus on the volume reduction at source in cognizance with pertinent section as cited above;
(b) request the Barangays (i) to enhance/adapt the Municipal ordinances pertaining to solid waste cited above; and (ii) without Materials Recovery Facility (MRF), to exert effort in establishing a functional MRF;
(c) exercise strong political will to implement the applicable ordinances pertaining to Solid Waste Management; and (d) request from the Sangguniang Bayan to update the penalties being imposed to include other sanctions which are actually being imposed, such as the rendition of community service; and (e) initiate the creation of a MENR Office or appoint a person other than the current designated MENRO, who will be responsible for the implementation of laws, rules and regulations pertinent to the environment and natural resources; and (f) in coordination with the Municipal Engineer to survey the MRF for the necessary improvements to enhance the efficiency within the facility.

We reiterated and supplemented the prior year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Acting Municipal Accountant to:
(a) exert extra effort in (i)withholding taxes from all suppliers and contractors paid through direct payment and; (ii) settling prior years’ tax liabilities to the BIR for the proper disposition of prior years’ accountabilities of the LGU;
(b) cause the settlement of the unremitted taxes identified above;
(c) henceforth, ascertain that all taxes withheld are remitted intact to the BIR; and
(d) make appropriate adjustment/amendments for the above-mentioned erroneous entries and others errors noted to reflect the correct balance of the tax liability account.

