We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations and made additional recommendations that the Local Chief Executive require officials concerned to:

implement the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), recognition of PPE found at the station, and disposition of non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances as laid out in COA Circular 2020-006;

       exert efforts to prepare the Property Cards and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards, respectively, starting with the current year’s acquisition and recent years’ acquisitions and aim for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPE items are covered;

       consider the creation of a permanent position in the GSO and accounting office to carry out regular functions, particularly the conduct of annual physical count and maintenance of property records;

       attend training relative to LRAMM by the DILG, to be able to adopt and follow the procedures set forth therein and eventually comply with the requirements thereof on reporting as prescribed under COA Circular 2015-008; and

prepare an Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property and Report of Waste Materials, where applicable, for unserviceable properties and request the same for disposal in accordance with the procedures mentioned above.

Additionally, we also reiterated the prior year’s audit recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:

instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant to review the noted transactions and prepare the appropriate adjusting journal entries to correct the misstatements of the affected accounts. Henceforth, ensure that costs of major repairs, rehabilitation, improvement, and construction of infrastructure assets should be capitalized or recognized as property, plant and equipment in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) No. 17 and related rules on asset recognition; and

direct the Municipal Budget Officer to adequately appropriate funds classified under Capital Outlays instead of allotments for MOOE in the LGU’s Annual Budget for transactions that are capital in nature such as construction and major repairs of buildings and infrastructures to facilitate the correct accounting recognition as required by Section 50 of Manual on NGAS for LGUs Volume I.

We also recommend that the LCE cause the designation of new members of the Inventory Committee to replace members who are separated from service for the improved efficiency and compliance by the Committee.

We reiterated and supplemented our prior year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:

direct all concerned individuals to stop the practice of using reimbursement for payment of gasoline but instead avail of the Purchase Order issued by the LGU or claim for travelling allowance for official trips undertaken; 

instruct concerned drivers to prepare a duly accomplished Driver’s Trip Ticket prior to travel;

require the GSO to prepare and submit Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption to properly monitor the fuel consumption of the LGU;

direct the Acting-Municipal Accountant to (i) check the completeness of the information provided in the trip ticket prior to allowing payment thereof; and (ii) strictly adhere to the regulations requiring the withholding and remittance of taxes withheld as prescribed by existing laws and regulations.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to: 

direct the Municipal Accountant to (i) see to it that funds held in trust are duly supported with MOA or equivalent document and that the disbursements are in accordance therewith; and (ii) effect the necessary entry in the GF to recognize the assets derecognized in the TF;
instruct the Local Finance Committee and the implementing departments to review and submit the noted deficiencies in item 1.7.; and (ii) on future similar undertaking, strictly adhere to the agreement or guidelines relative to the specific fund held in trust.

We reiterated and supplemented our recommendations and the Local Chief Executive, in coordination with the LDC and MPDO, agreed to:

continue the checking/regular monitoring of the fund’s utilization in harmony with the approved AIP; 

present in detail the PPAs charged under the 20% DF in the Annual Investment Program (AIP);

continuously refer to the JMC for appropriate guidance in crafting the Annual Investment Program and inclusion of PPAs on the 20% DF that will aim to fully attain the desired socio-economic development targets of the LGU; and

ensure consistency in the adequacy of allocation and continued adherence with the mandated utilization of the fund in accordance with pertinent provisions of the JMC.

We reiterated our previous year’s and made additional recommendations that the Local Chief Executive, thru the Designated MENRO:

intensify and sustain the current information drive and awareness campaign among the residents, in coordination with the Barangay, following the strategies identified under the approved 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan of the LGU and with focus on the volume reduction at source in cognizance with pertinent section as cited above;

exercise strong political will to implement the applicable ordinances pertaining to Solid Waste Management; 

request the Barangays (i) to enhance/adapt the Municipal ordinances pertaining to solid waste cited above; and (ii) without Materials Recovery Facility (MRF), to exert effort in establishing a functional MRF;

initiate the creation of MENR Office or appoint a person other than the current designated MENRO, who will be responsible for the implementation of laws, rules and regulations pertinent to the environment and natural resources.

We reiterated and supplemented the prior year’s recommendation and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Acting Municipal Accountant to:

continue with the efforts made on withholding and remittances of taxes in accordance with the aforequoted regulations;

look into the cause of the variances between the withheld amounts and remittances made and make the adjustments/amendments to BIR returns starting with current year variances, if necessary, to reflect the actual deductions based on specific reference months;

coordinate with the BIR for the proper disposition of prior years’ accountabilities of the LGU; 

henceforth, ascertain that taxes all withheld are remitted intact to the BIR; and

consider the employment of a permanent Municipal Accountant to oversee all the financial transactions of the Municipality, including the withholding and remittance of BIR and other mandated functions.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

require the Acting General Services Office Head and the Acting Municipal Accountant to (i) maintain Property Records and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards, respectively, starting with the current year’s acquisition and recent years’ acquisitions and aim for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPE items are covered; 

(ii) reconcile physical count results with property records and those maintained at the Accounting Office and isolate items not reconciled for easy reference in succeeding inventory taking; 

(iii) aim to reduce the number and amount of unreconciled PPE account balances; and 

(iv) strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records of the accounting, the property and actual inventory results

direct the Acting General Services Office Head to (i) prepare Acknowledgement Receipts for Equipment (ARE) for all PPE items, starting with current and recent years’ acquisitions until all items are covered and thereafter, renew the AREs at least every three years; 

(ii) facilitate the preparation of the inventory reports and the conduct of physical count and in the event that documents needed to obtain costing of PPE is no longer feasible, consider the fair value thereof as point of reference pursuant to PPSAS 17; and 

(iii) implement the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of inventory-taking and preparation of the RPCPPE, recognition of PPE found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances as laid out in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and

instruct the Municipal Engineer to conduct an initial inventory of local road networks in the Municipality in reference to the procedures set by COA Circular 2015-008.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

instruct the Acting GSO Head to process all purchasing concerns and keep track of the movement of stocks on hand from receipt until issuance for accounting, control and accountability purposes; 

consider in the budget preparation for the ensuing year, the provision of a storage room so that the procurement of supplies in significant quantities can be stored to lessen the administrative cost in frequent procurements and reimbursements;

require the Acting GSO Head to: (i) henceforth, prepare and submit documents on purchases of the Municipality; 

(ii) prepare and maintain stock cards for the purchased supplies; 
(iii) conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation; and (iv) procure, as far as practicable and feasible, directly from the DBM-PS all anticipated common-use supplies, and resort to local suppliers only upon unavailability of supplies needed; and

require the Acting Municipal Accountant to: 

